x4freetext: Weapons neutron research (WNR)
at LANSCE.
The neutrons are produced in a nat-W spallation
target driven by an 800-MeV proton beam.
Two sets of runs made with different samples; all
samples enriched to 99.798% 238U:
1) 1998: 238U foil, 730 mg/cm2 thick.
2) 1999: two 238U foils, 840 mg/cm2 thick in total,
along with 4 natural Fe foils, 2 in front and 2 in
back of the 238U foils.
GEANIE detector for gamma-rays.
235U and 238U fission chamber used to measure
neutron flux.
Corrected for:
. finite beam spot size,
. gamma attenuation in sample,
. deadtimes,
. internal conversion coefficients.
not corrected for secondary effects, such as multiple
scattering and emission of fission neutrons.
Statistical uncertainty.
Uncertainties in the gamma-ray
absorption in the sample, finite beam size effects, as
well as detector efficiency uncertainties 5-11%.
uncertainties in the fission foil thickness,
fission cross section, ionization chamber efficiency
the uncertainty in the neutron flux
uncertainty in target thickness
uncertainty in dead time corrections for
the detection of gamma rays
uncertainty in dead time corrections
for neutrons in the fission chamber
